                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="other">The Ogham inscription is apparently <q>not cut in relation to any precise arris, as for most of its height the edge of a chamfer is not obvious on this side</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 231-2). The Ogham inscription reads vertically upwards across the chamfer of the upper left edge of the stone, using the inner edge of the chamfer as an arris. The Ogham inscription was cut after the roman-letter inscription, obliterating part of it. The roman-letter inscription is in five lines, reading horizontally across. The third and fourth lines are apparently underscored. The roman-letter inscription was partially removed when the stone was chamfered on both edges of the stone. </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>Both inscriptions appear <rs type="execution" key="chiselled" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">chiselled</rs>. The Roman-letter inscription is described in the Welsh Corpus as <q>crude...showing no signs of regular ruling or letter-spacing...Of the three horizontal score-marks, only the third line of letters appears to use one as a guide. The three terminal Ss are different, the strokes put on so freely that the two diagonals of the last V do not meet</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 231-2).  
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
