            <div type="translation">               
                <div type="textpart" n="1" source="RED2007">
                    <p>Ogham: of <persName xml:lang="pgl">Taricoro</persName>?</p>
                </div>
                 <div type="textpart" n="2" source="TOM1975">
                <p>Latin: <persName xml:lang="la">Lucius [Annius] Taurianus</persName> lies here (Tomlin 1975)</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                        <p>It is impossible to recreate the first line of the Roman-letter inscription '[...]CIVS' as this is a very common name-ending. There are also a number of possible suggestions for the last name, including <persName xml:lang="la">Maurianus</persName>, <persName xml:lang="la">Taurianus</persName> and <persName xml:lang="la">Scaurianus</persName>. Thus, the recreation of the inscription for translation to English is subject to debate. Tomlin (1975) suggested that <q>with its arrangement in short horizontal lines, the medial stop after the S in the second line and the purely Latin character of its word-endings, this inscription appears to [be] sub-Roman rather than 'Early Christian' in character</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 231-3).</p>
                    <p>The ogham inscription is remarkable in being the only known example of an ogham inscription overlying a Latin one. It is further notable in that the two inscriptions do not appear to be related. The word/name in the inscription, TARICORO, is obscure but likely Irish. Thomas (1994) compares TARICORO with OI <foreign xml:lang="sg">Tairmesc</foreign> in which <foreign>Tair-</foreign> is prepositional. The Welsh Corpus notes that <q>a possible second element is <foreign>*kor-</foreign> 'cast, throw' (Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga">cuir-</foreign>)</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 231-3).</p>
            </div>
